  "assignment": {
    "taskDescription": "Analyze the deviation from Raoult's Law in a mixture of ethanol and acetone. Write a brief report (150-200 words) explaining why this specific mixture exhibits positive deviation, referencing intermolecular forces before and after mixing.",
    "rubric": [
      "Correctly identifies the type of deviation as 'positive' based on boiling point elevation or vapor pressure increase.",
      "Accurately describes hydrogen bonding in pure ethanol versus weaker dipole-dipole interactions in acetone.",
      "Explains that breaking strong H-bonds between ethanol molecules requires energy, leading to higher escaping tendency and increased vapor pressure.",
      "Concludes with a clear link between the weakened intermolecular forces in the mixture and the observed positive deviation."
    ],
    "answerKey": "The mixture of ethanol and acetone shows positive deviation from Raoult's Law. In pure ethanol, molecules are held together by strong hydrogen bonds. Acetone has dipole-dipole interactions but no H-bonding capability with itself in the same way. When mixed, the interaction between an ethanol molecule and an acetone molecule is weaker than the original ethanol-ethanol hydrogen bond. This weakening of intermolecular forces allows molecules to escape more easily into the vapor phase compared to pure components. Consequently, the total vapor pressure increases above the ideal value predicted by Raoult's Law, resulting in a positive deviation."
  }
}
